date:   2014-12-29 18:56:32

<p align="justify">
It is not a big deal however I want to add this to my notes. When executing the following simple factorial code which is written 
in Scala language, one can come across Stack Overflow with default Jvm settings. 
</p>

{% highlight Scala %}
    def factorial(n:Int):BigInt =
      if (n==0) 1
      else n * factorial(n-1)
{% endhighlight %}

<p align="justify">
On my local machine which is Windows 7 with Java HotSpot(TM) 64-Bit Server VM (build 24.71-b01, mixed mode) when I evaluate this line
</p>

{% highlight Scala %}
println("factorial 90000 = " + factorial(90000))
{% endhighlight %}

I get 

{% highlight Scala %}
Exception in thread "main" java.lang.StackOverflowError
	at java.math.BigInteger.<init>(BigInteger.java:963)
	at java.math.BigInteger.valueOf(BigInteger.java:957)
	at scala.math.BigInt$.apply(BigInt.scala:39)
	at scala.math.BigInt$.int2bigInt(BigInt.scala:97)
	at Factorial$.factorial$1(Factorial.scala:5)
{% endhighlight %}

How ever I can use the same stack over and over with the following Scala code.

{% highlight Scala %}
def factiorialTailRecursion(n: Int): BigInt = {
  def helper(x: Int, acc: BigInt): BigInt =
	if (x == 0) acc
	else helper(x - 1, x * acc)
  helper(n, 1)
}
{% endhighlight %}

And evaluating the same line gives me :
{% highlight Scala %}
factorial 90000 = 
{% endhighlight %}

without having the stack being overflowed with function calls.
